  "prompt": "Where can I rent a big apartment in Seattle and not pay too much money?",
  "response": "Seattle's rental market can be quite competitive, but there are neighborhoods where you might find more affordable options for a larger apartment. Here are some tips to help you find a more budget-friendly big apartment:\n\n1. **Neighborhoods to Consider:**\n   - **Beacon Hill:** This area can offer relatively lower rent prices compared to some of the more central neighborhoods.\n   - **Rainier Valley:** Another option that may offer a variety of apartment sizes at lower prices.\n   - **Delridge:** Situated in West Seattle, and often has more affordable rental rates.\n   - **Northgate:** Located in North Seattle, this area is undergoing redevelopment, providing potential deals on larger units.\n   - **West Seattle:** While some parts can be expensive, there are pockets where larger apartments are more affordable.\n\n2. **Look at Older Buildings:**\n   Older apartment buildings or complexes often have larger units with lower rent compared to newer developments.\n\n3. **Consider Sharing:**\n   Renting a larger space and sharing with roommates can significantly reduce individual costs.\n\n4. **Use Apartment Search Websites:**\n   Websites like Craigslist, Zillow, Apartments.com, or Rent.com can be useful for identifying available large apartments within your budget.\n\n5. **Check with Local Property Management Companies:**\n   Sometimes tapping into local property management companies can uncover available rentals before they\u2019re widely advertised.\n\n6. **Flexibility with Move-in Date:**\n   Sometimes rents can be lower during off-peak rental seasons, such as winter months.\n\n7. **Negotiation:**\n   See if there\u2019s room to negotiate for lower rent, especially if the apartment has been on the market for a while.\n\nRemember, while searching, prioritize safety and convenience concerning transportation and amenities.",
